Duration Calculations

Laura F White

2024-2-7

Methods

Estimation of the duration of disease

We leverage countries with two prevalence surveys to determine duration and incidence of TB each year between the two prevalence surveys. To do this, we use data on cures and deaths from TB for each country modeled here. We assume that the ratio of prevalence to incidence is not changing over the studied time period (which implies that disease duration is also not changing). As a first, most simple approach to this problem, we determine what the ratio of prevalence to incidence must be to get us to the value of the second prevalence survey. We calculate prevalence in year \(t\), \(P_t\) as a function of the prior years prevalence, number treated, number who died and the incidence in the prior year, as follows: \(P_t=P_{t-1}-C_{t-1}-D_{t-1}+I_{t-1}\), where \(C_t\) are the number of treated (or cured) cases of TB in year \(t\) and \(D_t\) are the number of deaths or self cures from TB in year \(t\). We assume that the number who die or self cure have an average duration of 5 years (though we run a sensitivity analysis for this) and estimate the size of this population to be \(D_t=(1/\delta_u)*(P_t-C_t)\), where \(\delta_u\) is the duration of untreated disease.

We observe prevalence at two time points and have annual treatment and mortality data.

We provide more detail on the estimates of prevalence for each country below. We couple prevalence per 100,000 individuals with the population level estimates when the prevalence surveys were conducted to get the total number of prevalent TB cases, which we use in our calculation.

We use an approach similar to sample importance resampling to estimate the duration of treated disease and run all analyses. We detail the approach here. First we use the confidence intervals for each prevalence survey estimate and assume normality to get a standard deviation for each prevalence survey value. We then run 10^{5} iterations of the following process. We then generate a potential first prevalence survey values from the normal distribution assumed from the prevalence estimate. We sample a possible duration of treated disease from a uniform(1,6) distribution. With these two values, we run our model to get an estimated second prevalence survey estimate. We then calculate the normal density value for these first and second prevalence survey values, using the estimated normal distribution. If we call these probabilities from the normal distribution \(p_{1i}\) and \(p_{2i}\) for iteration \(i\) then the weight is calculated as \(w_i=p_{1i}p_{2i}\). This means we get higher weights for scenarios that generate prevalence survey values that are closer to the observed values. We create normalized weights as \(\tilde{w}_i=\frac{w_i}{\sum w_i}\).

We use these normalized weights to generate a posterior distribution of the treated disease duration estimates. This is done by sampling 10^{4} values from the duration values sampled form the uniform distribution previously weighted by the normalized weights to get a posterior distribution of the duration of treated disease.

We perform a sensitivity analysis for the assumed duration of untreated duration of TB disease, \(\delta_u\). Our primary simulation assumes that this is 5 years. But we also run the simulations for values ranging from 3 to 7 years.
